article.description:
With each game that 
passes, the New Jersey Nets respond even more impressively to 
the Boston Celtics' frantic comebacks.

related.description:
If the Boston Celtics don't find a way to get off
to a better start, there is a greater chance their season will come
to a finish Friday night in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference
finals.

article.headline: Nets take over in fourth, gain 3-2 series lead
article.linkText: Nets thwart Celts rally, run away with Game 5
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- There's only one comeback the Boston Celtics need to worry about now in the Eastern Conference finals.
Kittles

Kidd

Coming back from a 3-2 deficit. The Celtics find themselves facing elimination after the New Jersey Nets weathered another hectic second-half rally by Boston for an emphatic 103-92 victory at Continental Airlines Arena on Wednesday night. The best-of-seven series returns to Boston on Friday for Game 6 at the unfriendly confines of the FleetCenter. One more win will send the top-seeded Nets to the NBA Finals for the first time in franchise history. "We are just trying to seize the moment," Nets forward Kenyon Martin said. "We came this far, so why stop playing?" "The hardest thing is to end the series," added Jason Kidd, who had 18 points, 12 rebounds and seven assists. "We know it's going to be a hostile environment. The toughest thing is to win on the road." Kerry Kittles scored 21 points to lead the Nets, but it was Keith Van Horn who delivered the knockout blows with back-to-back 3-pointers to cap a game-breaking 20-1 run in the final quarter. Van Horn and Martin both finished with 19 points. Paul Pierce had a game-high 24 points for Boston, but got little help from Antoine Walker, who scored 13 points on 5-of-20 shooting. Down by as much as 20 points in the second quarter and 55-38 at the half, the Celtics whittled the deficit to 72-69 after three quarters and pulled within one at 74-73 on two Erick Strickland free throws with 10:50 remaining. The ghost of Blown Fourth-Quarter Leads Past was again ready to visit the Nets, who blew the biggest fourth-quarter lead in NBA playoff history in a demoralizing Game 3 loss on Saturday. "Look, Boston is a good team -- they're going to make a run," Van Horn said. "They're just not going to lay down and die. We expect that. They have some players who won't quit. They're a team that never gives up and we understand that. "As long as we have that in the back of our minds, no matter what run they have, we need to just roll with it." Via the pick-and-roll, the Nets scored the next 13 points as part of a decisive 20-1 spurt. Kidd, as usual, served as the catalyst. Kidd scored six of the first 10 points during the run to push New Jersey out to an 84-73 cushion. Kidd sank an open jumper, dropped in a layup after driving through the Celtics' defense and put back Lucious Harris' missed jumper. "He's done it all season," said Martin of Kidd. "It's not a surprise anymore." Tony Battie sank one of two free throws to snap the Nets' 13-0 streak, but, after a Richard Jefferson free throw, Van Horn buried consecutive 3-pointers to extend New Jersey's lead to 94-74 with 5:35 to play. "They had a super game," Celtics coach Jim O'Brien said. "When we cut it to one, they held themselves together." The Celtics' offense fell apart when the Nets switched to a zone defense in the fourth quarter. Pierce, who missed a key free throw in the final seconds of Game 4, was held scoreless in the final period. "It threw off our rhythm a little bit," Walker said. "We were prepared for it, but not as much as they played it. They stopped our movement." The Nets worked their Princeton offense to perfection in the first half, routinely finding the open man with accurate skip passes over Boston's pack-it-in defense. They actually shot better from the field (55 percent) than the free-throw line (50 percent). Meanwhile, the Celtics made just 11 of their 41 first-half attempts (27 percent) and only three of 16 3-pointers (19 percent). Pierce and Walker combined for 20 points on 5-for-21 shooting in the first half. Drives to the basket and perfect free-throw shooting (8 for 8) enabled Pierce to score 12 points; Walker had eight points but missed 11 of his 14 first-half attempts. Before the series, Pierce boasted that the Nets couldn't defend him. He carried a much more humbled tone after being hounded by New Jersey's double teams for the second straight game. "They're changing up the defense, throwing two or three guys at me when I drive," said Pierce, who averaged 37 points against New Jersey in four regular-season games. "But I feel like I'm getting a lot of good looks and finding guys when the opportunity is there. I'm just trying not to really force it. ... When another man is open and someone is trapped down on me, I try to find him." Boston, in dire need of a third scoring option behind Pierce and Walker, found one in Strickland in the third quarter. Banished to the bench since the first-round series win over Philadelphia, Strickland scored nine of Boston's last 11 points in the third to help shave New Jersey's lead to just three at 72-69. Strickland, who had gone scoreless in 11 minutes of action in the series before Wednesday, contributed 13 points off the bench. "We have been putting ourselves in holes early on and have been fighting so hard to get back into the game," Strickland said. "We just ran out of gas tonight." The Celtics hoped to get off to a fast start for a change but couldn't avoid their first-period doldrums. They shot a miserable 21.1 percent from the field (4 of 19) to fall behind 31-16 after one. Pierce and Walker were a combined 2-for-11, but Pierce's persistent drives to the hoop got him to the line to shoot a perfect 6-of-6 in his eight-point first quarter. Boston trimmed its deficit to 35-28 against Kidd and the Nets' second unit, but New Jersey responded with a 15-2 run to push its lead to 20 at 50-30. Kittles, who had 12 first-quarter points, capped the run with a running floater through the lane with 3:03 left in the half. "We know we're hurting ourselves by letting them get out to fast starts. We realize that," Pierce said. "We continue to talk about it, but we're not doing it. But we've got a chance on Friday to tie the series up and come back here for Game 7. We feel like the series is far from over." Game notes
The Celtics' bench was outscored 71-53. ... The Nets are 5-0 in the playoffs when scoring 100 points or more. ... Kittles led the Nets in scoring for the third straight game. He is averaging 20.6 points during the stretch. Joe Lago is the NBA editor for ESPN.com.
